<br>
1.  The Republican right wish the US to control the middle-east, (and by extension, the oil supply.)<br>
<br>
2.  The big oil companies want and need Iraq's oil to start flowing again.<br>
<br>
Everything else (WMDs, the brutality of Saddam's regime, human rights, 9/11, whatever) was just incidental and provided the perfect excuse.  Sorry if that's unpalatable to you, but it is the truth.<br>
<br>
Whatever the result of the conflict, and it's potential long-term benefits for the Iraqi people, our respective governments <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>have</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> misled us (both the British and American public) about why they wanted to oust Saddam. That to me is just simple truth, and I personally prefer to face up to it, whatever anyone else may think.<br>
<br>
Also true is the fact that the US (and UK) have supported many repressive regimes with appalling human rights records throughout the last century, (and will no doubt continue to do so, as long as the said regimes do not threaten the US (or UK) economic interest.)<br>
<br>
Euro-snob?  Oh that must be an American expression, new to me I'm afraid<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->      <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->      <br>
But timberwind, judging from the number of my remarks that you have quoted out of context and with such strident sardonicism, I would say that it is I who seem to have &quot;touched a nerve&quot;<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->       And as for Dusty's thoughtful and logical analysis (which I am sure was only ever meant to be a musing on the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>possible</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> course of events) you will I hope notice that very early on in it he said:-<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I would expect the plan to involve initial massive air strikes followed by a rapid armoured assault on Baghdad. The hope, I imagine, will be that the (hopefully) demoralised Iraqi army will mutiny, or even rebel, leaving the city, and Sad, undefended!<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Is this not in fact precisely what has occurred, more or less?<br>
<br>
I also mourn the dead, (and I also do not care what anyone thinks of that feeling.)  And if you cannot, then I genuinely feel sorry for you. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=talche>Talche</A> at: 4/11/03 3:08:35 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 136<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/12/03 3:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=405.topic&index=62>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: We are winning!</span><hr size=1> I am still here (though I wasn’t during the week. I was up in London with no PC access) It would appear that the US advance into Baghdad (and the other cities) has been remarkably successful, and I am glad for that. The less people who die the better (But beware of Triumphalisim, There is plenty yet to do to win the peace)<br>
<br>
However I feel my original assessment still stands. The plan was a valid one even if it wasn’t actually what eventually happened. Obviously I can’t really say if Sadham was trying my plan or not. If he had been, he screwed it up by leaving his best forces out in the open, vulnerable to air attack, rather than withdrawing them to the heavily built up parts of Baghdad as soon as the air raids started. (but that’s a subject for another thread!)<br>
<br>
Ultimately, Baghdad was “taken” Not because the US successfully stormed it but, because, when it came to the crunch, it wasn’t really defended! Even with the limited weapons at the Iraqis disposal, had Baghdad been systematically defended the coalition forces would have been badly hurt! And probably held at bay for some considerable time.<br>
<br>
We all saw the footage of the burning M1, I understand that the tank was disabled by an RPG, I also understand that, thankfully, the crew escaped and that the tank was subsequently destroyed by the US to prevent it from falling into enemy hands. BUT it was still disabled by a $5 rocket launcher, just like I said they could be!<br>
<br>
What we didn’t see on TV was a similar incident in Basra where a British C2 had its “wings pulled off” by Iraqis using RPG’s. They didn’t de-track it but they did manage to damage the hull machine guns and the targeting and communications array effectively rendering it useless, all using cheap RPG’s!<br>
<br>
A better organised and more determined defence would have caused us heavy casualties!<br>
<br>
(Insofar as *any* of this is funny, I was highly amused so see the way that reporters initially “assumed” that the burning tank was an Iraqi one. I mean. It couldn’t *possibly* have been a mighty American one could it?<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rollin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/roll.gif ALT=":rollin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
<br>
The reason why we have had this success in Iraq is because Iraqi forces morale collapsed. (Yes the regime did, eventually, implode but perhaps not as soon as expected. I’ll take a small portion of Timberwinds crow for that! And I am happy to Eat it while its still warm) But it wasn’t because we defeated them as such. They just didn’t want to fight any more! there are many reasons for this. As with the reasons for the war in the first place there is no single reason, but in no particular order, Ill try to list some of the ones that come to mind.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">The siege</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.<br>
<br>
(I see you all scratching your heads wondering what the hell I am talking about)<br>
<br>
Oh yes, the siege. Until the more widespread footage of Baghdad became available over the last few days I had failed to appreciate simply how destitute Baghdad actually was (and the other Iraqi cities for that matter) the reason for this destitution is debateable but 12 years of UN sanctions (“Sanctions” sounds so much more civilised than “siege” but the effect is the same) combined with Sadhams brutal internal policies have caused immense suffering and poverty for millions of people. <br>
<br>
I imagine after all this; even those who supported Sadham would simply be grateful for it all to be over. They would fight for a while but at the end of the day their hearts would not really be in it. Eventually many of them would simply want to go back to their families.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">A Nation divided</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
Another problem is that Iraq is deeply divided, in any brutal dictatorship nobody trusts anybody and everybody watches everybody else (CIA, FBI, NSA, etc. etc! Ermm! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) C &amp; C is heavily centralised. Local commanders are not entrusted with either the authority or information to make their own decisions. If Command and communications are damaged (as was US policy in Iraq) it is quite possible to disorient troops at the front so much so that, no matter how brave they are, organised defence becomes impossible with the only remaining option being small scale guerrilla operations (which could well go on for a long time, don’t assume this is over just yet!)<br>
<br>
Bombing alone would be unlikely to cause this collapse of morale (It never has in the past) but it could certainly destroy the command chain and, in a dictatorship, this would be very damaging.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">The city layout.</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
Again I had not fully appreciated how “open “ Baghdad is.  It is a large city but unlike European cities its layout for the most part is a patchwork quilt of small communities and market gardens (I don’t know if the US uses that term, if not, it means small urban farms producing mainly vegetables and fruit)<br>
<br>
This city layout favoured the “reconnaissance by sortie” tactic. The open nature of Bagdad meant that rapid “drive by shootings” were a relatively safe tactic for allied forces. Once it was established that there was going to be no serious resistance, more determined advances could be made eventually resulting in the occupation (but not nececarrily the control! There is still a lot of fighting going on) of central Baghdad.<br>
<br>
What happens next?<br>
<br>
As I write this Mosel has fallen, more or less without a shot being fired. but Tikrit is not really being talked about. It seems to be the last stronghold of Sadhams supporters How long they will hold out and whether or not he is there, who knows?<br>
<br>
My greatest concern now is that, sooner or later, the differing Iraqi factions will start fighting each other. Iraqi citizens are heavily armed. Indeed, as I am writing this, BBC news is reporting fighting between Sunni and Sheia militias in Baghdad, if this gets out of hand there will be little we can do about it! After the toppling of a brutal regime like this, there runs the serious risk of celebrations developing into a “Terror” as old scores are settled.<br>
<br>
The US will, indeed, have most of their armed forces “Bogged down” in Iraq for some time, The idea that we will be able to have elections, democracy and Big Macs sometime soon seems to me to be very remote. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START |I --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tired.gif ALT="|I"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
